### Define Convex Database Schema (TypeScript)

Source: https://docs.convex.dev/database

Shows how to define a schema for your Convex database using TypeScript. This example defines a 'messages' table with 'author' (a reference to a 'users' table) and 'body' (a string) fields. It utilizes `defineSchema`, `defineTable`, and `convex/values`.

```typescript
import {
  defineSchema,
  defineTable
} from "convex/server";
import {
  v
} from "convex/values";

// @snippet start schema
export default defineSchema({
  messages: defineTable({
    author: v.id("users"),
    body: v.string(),
  }),
});
```

--------------------------------

### Define Convex Cron Jobs with Intervals and Specific Schedules (TypeScript)

Source: https://docs.convex.dev/scheduling/cron-jobs

This snippet demonstrates how to define cron jobs in Convex using TypeScript. It shows how to schedule functions to run at regular intervals (e.g., every minute) and at specific times (e.g., monthly). It utilizes the `cronJobs` utility from `convex/server` and refers to internal Convex functions.

```typescript
import { cronJobs } from "convex/server";
import { internal } from "./_generated/api";

const crons = cronJobs();

crons.interval(
  "clear messages table",
  { minutes: 1 }, // every minute
  internal.messages.clearAll,
);

crons.monthly(
  "payment reminder",
  { day: 1, hourUTC: 16, minuteUTC: 0 }, // Every month on the first day at 8:00am PST
  internal.payments.sendPaymentEmail,
  { email: "my_email@gmail.com" }, // argument to sendPaymentEmail
);

// An alternative way to create the same schedule as above with cron syntax
crons.cron(
  "payment reminder duplicate",
  "0 16 1 * *",
  internal.payments.sendPaymentEmail,
  { email: "my_email@gmail.com" }, // argument to sendPaymentEmail
);

export default crons;

```

--------------------------------

### Convex Action with Context for Database Interaction (Mutation)

Source: https://docs.convex.dev/functions/actions

This example demonstrates using `ctx.runMutation` within a Convex Action to execute an internal mutation. It shows how to pass arguments to the mutation and potentially use its returned data.

```typescript
import { v } from "convex/values";
import { action } from "./_generated/server";
import { internal } from "./_generated/api";

export const doSomething = action({
  args: { a: v.number() },
  handler: async (ctx, args) => {
    const data = await ctx.runMutation(internal.myMutations.writeData, {
      a: args.a,
    });
    // do something else, optionally use `data`
  },
});
```

--------------------------------

### Define Convex Internal Mutation with Manual Argument Type Annotation in TypeScript

Source: https://docs.convex.dev/understanding/best-practices/typescript

This example shows how to define an internal Convex mutation in TypeScript by manually annotating the arguments type. This is useful for internal functions with complex argument structures. It requires importing `internalMutation` from './_generated/server'.

```typescript
import { internalMutation } from "./_generated/server";

export default internalMutation({
  // To convert this function from JavaScript to
  // TypeScript you annotate the type of the arguments object.
  handler: async (ctx, args: { body: string; author: string }) => {
    const { body, author } = args;
    await ctx.db.insert("messages", { body, author });
  },
});
```

--------------------------------

### Define a Simple HTTP Action Handler in Convex

Source: https://docs.convex.dev/functions/http-actions

This code shows how to define an HTTP action handler using the `httpAction` constructor in Convex. The handler is an asynchronous function that can perform operations within the Convex environment and returns a Response object.

```typescript
import { httpAction } from "./_generated/server";

export const doSomething = httpAction(async () => {
  // implementation will be here
  return new Response();
});
```

